content.description: The face to the left of Prehension. Balance moves and small holds make up yet another tough Blue Mounds 5.9. Few rests can be found and the climb is pumpy, so move fast. (Update: Upgraded to 5.10c in the 2012 M. Farris guide).
content.protection: Standard TR set up - long slings are helpful.

content.description:
This route is the most obvious must do (along with prehension) at this wall so you had better give it a try! 

  The Thumbnail Direct begins in the alcove feature with a steep crack. Although the technical crux on this route is the first few moves, the final half of the route is mentally difficult due to hard to protect moves with iffy wires.
is pretty sustained 5.10 climbing the crux is the middle section trying to find feet.
content.protection: typical blue mounds top rope set up would not recommend leading this route
content.location: puzzle foot is between prehension and thumbnail direct go up 5 feet to gain ledge then start with the fun smooth face crimps and side pulls this climb will get you pumped

content.description: Prominent wide crack up the center of Table Rock Buttress.  It seemed like 5.7 climbing the whole way up rather than a distinct crux.
content.protection: Standard TR set up, long slings helpful.

content.description: Less frequented than Prairie Walls and other areas but one of the better rocks of the Receding Ramparts. There is a flat boulder in front of it a little ways as the name suggests. Usually has a nice grassy surface at the base of the routes too.
